As the ODE is separable, we can re-express with the differentials
separated:

\begin{align*}\displaystyle
(x^2+1) dx = (t^2+1) dt\end{align*} which can be integrated to yield

\begin{align*}\int (x^2+1) dx = \frac{x^3}{3} + x = \int (t^2+1) dt = \frac{t^3}{3} + t + C\end{align*}

We merge the two integration constants to \emph{C}. From our initial
condition that $x(0) = -1$ we obtain

\begin{align*}\displaystyle \frac{(-1)^3}{3} - 1 = \frac{0^3}{3} + 0 + C\end{align*}

and hence \emph{C = -4/3}. Left in implicit form the solution reads

\begin{align*}\frac{x^3}{3} + x = \frac{t^3}{3} + t - \frac{4}{3}\end{align*}
